<br>
As far as what system you use, nothing is going to please EVERYONE, but I think the simplest method is generally the best.  Even though my main is level 65 I don't think the idea to give characters more rolls for being higher level is a smart one.  The influence their level makes on the success of the raid isn't likely to be three times greater than a lower level character's participation.  Awarding multiple items to a single person while some receive nothing is also a recipe for animosity and malcontent.<br>
<br>
Generally speaking, most people are happy with being able to win only a single item, but if the item they receive is droppable and a loot item they would prefer becomes available they can &quot;trade up&quot; by rolling on the new item, and giving the droppable item they won previously back to the raid for re-rolling when they win the new item.  While this may lead to a couple of re-rolls on loot, it makes everyone happy because they then know they have the option to roll on everything without sacrificing their chance at something REALLY useful to them.<br>
<br>
Personally, I am all in favor of NBG as well, but I can see how amongst a complete &quot;pick up&quot; crowd it would be difficult to manage.  If you are still inclined to provide a measure to promote those that can use an item being more likely to receive it as a reward, you could opt to use weighted rolls.  I.E. &quot;Ok, Armor piece_X dropped.  Everyone except melee that can wear it roll 1-1000, those that can equip it roll 1-1100&quot;, etc.  More than anything this is just a morale-booster, while everyone gets a chance to roll anyways, it shows you are at least taking some measure to give those that can actually equip and use the loot a better chance of winning it.<br>
<br>
